               <interp inst="t18430821-2529" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430821"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430821-2529" type="date" value="18430821"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430821-2529-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2529-18430821 t18430821-2529-offence-1 t18430821-2529-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2529. <persName id="def1-2529-18430821" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2529-18430821" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2529-18430821" type="age" value="40"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2529-18430821" type="surname" value="VALENTINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2529-18430821" type="given" value="FERDINAND"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FERDINAND VALENTINE</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430821-2529-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2529-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2529-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18430821-cd-281" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430821-2529-offence-1 t18430821-cd-281"></join>22nd of May</rs>, 1 guitar, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 time-pieces, 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 4 handkerchiefs, 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 brushes, 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 pair of scissors, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 stocks, 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 pair of drawers, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 accordions, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 copper-plates, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 2 pearl fish, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 shaving-cases, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 2 rules, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 breast-pin, 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 shaving-brush, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 waist-coats, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 pairs of trowsers, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 ring, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 2 pattern-books, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 pieces of leather, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1 coat, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 1 fish-slice, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1 pair of tongs, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 2 books, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18430821-name-1588" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1588" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1588" type="surname" value="ALBERT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1588" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430821-2529-offence-1 t18430821-name-1588"></join>Henry William Albert</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1589" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1589" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1589" type="surname" value="ALBERT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1589" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM ALBERT</persName>
                  </hi>. In 1841 I carried on business in London, as a merchant—I had offices in Oxford-court, Cannon-street, City. On the 19th of May I left this country—before I left, I engaged the prisoner as my clerk, at 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. per week—I paid him 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. the day before I went to France—I was away till August—in the interval some letters passed between me and him—I took a list of every thing I had in my office—I had a trunk in my counting-house, containing waistcoats, trowsers, handkerchiefs, stockings, and a ring, and I left a guitar and time-piece in my private room—I locked the trunk, and put the key into my cash-box, and the key of my cash-box I took with me—the cash-box I put into the office—I did not give the prisoner authority to open the trunk, and take any of the things, or to sell or pawn any—I returned in August, and saw the prisoner—he advised me not to go to my office, as I should be arrested for debt—I saw Duke, who was a friend of mine, and the prisoner together—I left it to them to try to arrange with my creditors—I staid in London a long time without going to my office—the prisoner came to we many times, and said, "You are watched from morning till night, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210208"></xptr>
               <p>You must not come"—I went at last, about six weeks before I had the pri<lb></lb>soner taken—I saw my box three weeks after—it was locked—I asked my landlord to break it open—I found there was nothing left in it—all my other things were gone—I afterwards found the prisoner, and had him taken—the things I lost were worth more than 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I went with a policeman to the pri<lb></lb>soner's house, and there found the key of my trund, and the duplicates and other things.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILDE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What do you deal in? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I take goods from France—I have no office at clerks now—I had an office in Falcon-square—I paid 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a quater for it—I lived there six months—I went from there to Oxford-court—I was there six years—in 1839 I was ruined, and took the benefit of the act—I then gave my name as James Henry Albert—I did not take my oath to the proceedings as Jew—I am a Protestant—I did not give my name as Jacob—when I went away I gave authority to the prisoner to carry on my business in Oxford-court, and left my office in his occupation—I paid him no money except the two weeks' salsry in advance—he was subject to expences on my behalf—I was in constant communication with him when I was at Paris—I know a person named Scalinger—Ihave seen him before with the prisoner—I have not been with him and the prisoner playing at cards—I have not been in friendly communication with the pri<lb></lb>soner since I found this out—I know a Mr. Hill, Mr. Hobler's clerk—I have quarrel with the prisoner—I had a private quarrel at the Eight Bells—it was not about this business.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are these razors and other things yours? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I did not find the cash-box at all—in it was the key of the trunk and a bill of Emboucheres—I know a person named Sheeler—I sas him many times before I went to Paris—I lost the key of my cash-box at paris—Sheeler was not present when I gave the prisoner the key.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was your cash-box like this one? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I cannot swear to this being it—(<hi rend="italic">looking at one.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1590" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1590" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1590" type="surname" value="GREAVES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1590" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN GREAVES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable G</hi> 46.) I was called on the 3rd of July to take the prisoner—the prosecutor told him it was for robbing him of wearing apparel and other articles—the prisoner made no answer—I went with him to his lodgings in Warwick-place, Whitecross-street, and found two time-pieces, a dressing-case, a gold ring, a pin, and some other things which the prosecutor claimed—the prisoner said nothing—I also found fourteen dupli<lb></lb>cates and a key, which the prosecutor swears to as belonging to his box.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Were these all about the room? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; the time-piece was going at the time, over the mantel-piece.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1591" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1591" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1591" type="surname" value="WILSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1591" type="given" value="LEONARD"></interp>LEONARD WILSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Mr. Russell, a pawnbroker in Fore-street—nine of these duplicates were given by our house, for a pair of trowsers, three waistcoats, and a stocks, pawned on the 20th of April, 1842; two boots, pawned on the 30th of April; a tea caddy the 4th of June; a Ger<lb></lb>man silver fish slice and tongs on the 13th of June; two accordians on the 18th of June; and a time-piece on the 27th of June; the whole amount is 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—they were pawned by a man—I cannot say who—the prisoner has pleged things, and has renewed tickets.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1592" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1592" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1592" type="surname" value="ALBERT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1592" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM ALBERT</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This is the key of my trunk that I left in my cash-box—these things are all mine—it is possible some of them were taken from my place and pawned before I left—I never gave the pri<lb></lb>soner authority to pledge any of these.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210209"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You swear to the trowsers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yet; theft it no mark on them, hut I have worn them often.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILDE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1593" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1593" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1593" type="surname" value="DROOP"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1593" type="given" value="IGNATIUS"></interp>IGNATIUS DROOP</persName>
                  </hi>. I conduct my aunt's business as a merchant—I know both the prisoner and the prosecutor—I remember the prosecutor going abroad—I lent him some money to go—he said he was going to fetch his cousin—I saw him, just previous to his going, give up the key of his cash-box to the prisoner, and tell him every thing he left in his possession, and to do the same as he did—I had a bill to indorse, and he asked the prisoner to indorse it—I said I had rather have his signature.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where do you live? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In Tower Royal, and I have a country house at Laytonstone—I have been in this country about eight years—I have never been in business for myself—the prosecutor told me that every thing the prisoner did was as if he did it himself—he told me that at Oxford-court—the prisoner was there, and there was a gentleman in his private room, with the door shut—I do not know his name—he went with the prosecutor to Paris—I have seen the key of the cash-box in the prisoner's possession since—I never saw him take the key of the trunk out of the cash-box—I saw him open the cash-box, after the prosecutor was gone, with the key that the prosecutor gave him—I went to him next day, because I forgot two bills of 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and he opened the cash-box—I never saw him open the trunk—I do not know any<lb></lb>thing about opening the tea-caddy on the 4th of June—the prisoner was in my aunt's service for some months as clerk—I took him about six months after the prosecutor went—our former clerk's name was Smith—he died—I saw the prosecutor when he returned in August, and showed him the door of our office, and forbad him to come—I told him there was a person named Mullens, whom he owed money to, would take out a writ against him—I did not tell him, if he went to his office in Oxford-court, he would be arrested by a sheriff's officer—I swear that I did not tell him there was a sheriff's officer watching for him, or that it would not be safe for him to go to his office—I did not tell the prosecutor to wait patiently till bis affairs came round—he did not say he would go to bis creditors and state to them what goods he had sent from Paris to the prisoner, and what property he had left at hit office—he laid he should resign himself and his property to his creditors—I did not say I hoped he would not act unkindly by me, at he knew the business was my aunt's, and not mine—I did not tell him I would provide him with money to go to Jersey, and set up business there—I said, "I don't know what you do here; you owe me a deal of money; if you were worth anything they would take you"—he told me he would go abroad, but he did not—I have been to the prisoner's lodgings once, just to see where he lives—I have not received from him any of the prosecutor's property—the property which I re<lb></lb>ceived from him belonged to me—it was property which the prosecutor had bought, and I had accepted bills and paid them honestly—it was bought of a merchant at Vienna—I received property of the prisoner after the prosecutor left England—it was property which the prosecutor had bought and paid for.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILDE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What does he owe you now? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> 311<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I am not a man of substance—I have been in business seven years and a half.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1594" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1594" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1594" type="surname" value="SULLINOTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1594" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH SULLINOTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a fancy trimming-maker. When the prosecu<lb></lb>tor returned from Paris I went to meet him, as the prisoner had no money—he begged of me to do so; and as at that time of year we were very slack in business, I went to Dover—I met the prosecutor—the prisoner went first, and they came into the public-house where I was—they kept on quarrelling—I said, "I don't like to hear this, the landlord will turn us out"—the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210210"></xptr>
               <p>prosecutor complained of the prisoner leaving the office—I said, "what was he to do; you left him 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."—he said, "That is right"—I said, "How could he keep on the office? you sent him letters and things; how could he keep on?"—he said, "Did I not leave him the trunk full of things? if he wanted he could have made money"—the prisoner said, "Of course I did; but what of that? that was not enough to keep me and pay letters and all and then I left the office"—I called at the prisoner's room on a Sunday morn<lb></lb>ning, and saw Mr. Hill there—I was not there above two minutes when the pro<lb></lb>secutor came in—Hill began some conversation, and the prisoner said, "You had better go home to dinner"—I looked up, and said, "I don't think your clock is right"—Mrs. Valentine said, "It is not right, it was not wound up"—the prisoner took out his watch and said, "It is not right."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where do you carry on business? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In Brudenell-place, New North-road—this is my first quarter—I have got the lease of the house—I came from Shoreditch—I have been six years in this country—I have known the prisoner three or four years—he has never been in my service—he is no relation of mine—when I met the prosecutor at Dover, I did not tell him it was not safe for him to go to his counting-house—I went to Dover because the prisoner had a letter from the prosecutor to meet him—I paid the expenses—I went down with the prisoner—I said, "I will pay my expenses, but you must pay for yourself "—he said, "Mr. Albert will pay you again,"but he has not—I left them at Dover—I did not hear the prisoner tell the prose<lb></lb>cutor it would not be safe to come to London—Valentine said, "What did you write for me to come here? you might as well have left me at home"—I then asked what was the matter, and he said the prisoner had left the office, which he has no business to do—he <hi rend="italic">blowed</hi> him <hi rend="italic">up</hi> for not putting on his best clothes—the prisoner said, "Don't you know I have pledged everything you left at home; but was that sufficient?"—the prosecutor said he should have managed somehow to have kept the office open.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1595" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1595" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1595" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1595" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>FRANCIS HILL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an attorney's clerk, and have been an attorney—I have been employed by the prisoner to negociate some misunderstandings between him and the prosecutor—I had instructions to meet the prosecutor at the latter end of Feb. or beginning of March—I went to his lodgings, and saw him—he did not expect me—we had some conversation—he appointed for me to come on the following morning at a quarter before nine o'clock—I went—he said, "What have you to say?"—I said, "I think you had better settle it; you claim money of him, and he does of you; if you will meet him at Oxford-court to-morrow, and give up some letters, all will be settled"—he appointed for me to call again, and I did—he was gone out—I told him the prisoner was willing to waive his claim to his salary, if he would give up his documents and the receipt for his goods.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> For whom did you act? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> As a friend—the prisoner had the goods either in his possession or under his control—he did not tell me he had pawned some—I did not tell the prosecutor he had pawned any—the prosecutor was looking at a list of the articles when I called on Sunday morning—he said, "These are the things that I left"—I said, "You are aware that he parted with some"—he said, "I don't know; all I want is my things back."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILDE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you been to the prisoner's lodgings, and seen the clock over the mantel-piece? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the prosecutor has been there—and seen the trowsers and things about.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>—<hi rend="smallCaps">COLLINS</hi>. Albert rented an office of me—he went abroad in May—the prisoner discontinued his attendance there about July, at my request—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210211"></xptr>
               <p>found there was no rent, and the persons were coming for money—he was regular in his attendance till about a fortnight before he left—I broke open the trunk at the prosecutor's request.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILDE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did the prisoner conduct himself with propriety? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, to me—the whole of the furniture was mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18430821-2529-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2529-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430821-2529-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi>. Aged 40.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy.</hi>
                  </rs>—
